00:49:36,651 --> 00:49:42,233
[SPEAKER_13]: You're time sensitive, but I do think that's a real... So it is something.

578
00:49:42,993 --> 00:49:45,874
[SPEAKER_05]: So ward representation may result

579
00:49:47,610 --> 00:49:50,632
[SPEAKER_05]: in unequal workloads.

580
00:49:52,114 --> 00:49:53,875
[SPEAKER_05]: Want to just say it like that, or you want to say it?

581
00:49:53,895 --> 00:49:56,617
[SPEAKER_14]: That sounds right for now, yeah.

582
00:49:57,258 --> 00:49:57,898
[SPEAKER_14]: Do we have an idea?

583
00:49:57,918 --> 00:49:59,199
[SPEAKER_12]: I'm sorry, can I ask a question?

584
00:50:00,420 --> 00:50:02,862
[SPEAKER_14]: Yeah, and then I, go ahead.

585
00:50:03,042 --> 00:50:04,824
[SPEAKER_14]: And then I think, was that Aubrey that I heard?

586
00:50:05,664 --> 00:50:05,824
[SPEAKER_14]: Yeah.

587
00:50:06,305 --> 00:50:08,707
[SPEAKER_14]: Okay, so Anthony, and go ahead.

588
00:50:10,428 --> 00:50:15,112
[SPEAKER_12]: Hi, I guess this is my question more for the connoisseurs.

589
00:50:16,065 --> 00:50:32,401
[SPEAKER_12]: when we get deep into this ward representation stuff, is there a way of combining wards and having four ward counselors and, say, five at-large counselors?

590
00:50:32,862 --> 00:50:40,149
[SPEAKER_12]: So when we talk about wards, and we're a small city, and you'll have one side of the street

591
00:50:41,020 --> 00:51:02,191
[SPEAKER_12]: in one ward and the other side of the street in a different ward, you know, is there a way of, you know, kind of doing like East, North, you know, West kind of, you know, just like four, four, well, I guess they wouldn't be wards would be, you know, kind of different sections rather than the eight at-large councils.

592
00:51:02,211 --> 00:51:05,713
[SPEAKER_12]: Because I think that would be a drastic change to our city.

593
00:51:07,592 --> 00:51:12,476
[SPEAKER_04]: So I'd start this with a quick preface.

594
00:51:12,496 --> 00:51:16,840
[SPEAKER_04]: So this body should just be aware that it's not going to draw the ward boundaries.

595
00:51:16,960 --> 00:51:21,483
[SPEAKER_04]: It can specify a number of wards, but it's not going to actually draw the boundaries.

596
00:51:22,604 --> 00:51:27,908
[SPEAKER_04]: Now, to your point, the wards are comprised of a certain number of precincts.

597
00:51:28,309 --> 00:51:30,791
[SPEAKER_04]: And again, like we said before, they have to be of an equal number.

598
00:51:31,231 --> 00:51:34,574
[SPEAKER_04]: So you can divide, you can decide the numbers, right?

599
00:51:36,015 --> 00:51:42,663
[SPEAKER_04]: You can increase the, I guess, in theory, you could increase the number of words or decrease the number of words as long as they all have approximately the same population.

600
00:51:45,025 --> 00:51:48,910
[SPEAKER_04]: And then, you know, somewhere down the line, someone else will.

601
00:51:50,151 --> 00:51:51,493
[SPEAKER_04]: You know, actually draw the lines.

602
00:51:53,663 --> 00:52:04,132
[SPEAKER_04]: So the short answer to your question is, yes, you can have a, if I understand your question correctly, you could have four wards, you could have the current number of wards, I forget what that is now.

603
00:52:04,552 --> 00:52:04,692
[SPEAKER_14]: Eight.

604
00:52:05,213 --> 00:52:07,735
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah, you could have the eight wards, things of that nature.

605
00:52:10,598 --> 00:52:12,679
[SPEAKER_14]: I'll just say one thing about that, Anthony.

606
00:52:12,960 --> 00:52:16,543
[SPEAKER_14]: When I was looking at Lowell, as their settlement,

607
00:52:17,485 --> 00:52:45,135
[SPEAKER_14]: they actually have eight wards as well, and they now have eight ward counselors and three at large, but for school committee, they have the same size school committee as we do, but they, I'm just gonna get this right, four are ward and two are at large, and the four that are ward, one city school committee member is from a combined

608
00:52:46,326 --> 00:52:47,346
[SPEAKER_14]: two combined wards.

609
00:52:47,466 --> 00:52:48,867
[SPEAKER_14]: And I think that's what you're asking about.

610
00:52:49,367 --> 00:53:03,470
[SPEAKER_14]: But I also will say that when I did have a conversation with the Lowell city clerk, and he told me they had to hire a specialist because if you're gonna start combining wards, you have to make sure that what you do follows state law.

611
00:53:04,931 --> 00:53:06,811
[SPEAKER_04]: So that- It's a complicated process.

612
00:53:07,091 --> 00:53:08,372
[SPEAKER_14]: Yes, yes.

613
00:53:08,472 --> 00:53:12,893
[SPEAKER_14]: So I think it can be done, but it's not generally done.

614
00:53:12,953 --> 00:53:14,393
[SPEAKER_14]: And if you do it, you have to,

615
00:53:15,254 --> 00:53:21,096
[SPEAKER_14]: make sure you're following the law and somebody with more knowledge than us would have to figure it out.

616
00:53:21,656 --> 00:53:30,480
[SPEAKER_08]: Right, because you could run afoul of the Voting Rights Act if you dilute a ward that's minority majority, like we have one.

617
00:53:32,580 --> 00:53:44,865
[SPEAKER_07]: Yeah, for analogy's sake, if you're following the news about Alabama, today's news was that from a congressional standpoint,

618
00:53:45,683 --> 00:53:59,377
[SPEAKER_07]: their districts were thrown out in federal court, and they were allowed to go back and redraw them, but the court found that they are still not properly representing the population.

619
00:53:59,837 --> 00:54:07,065
[SPEAKER_07]: They only had only one minority-majority district, and so the court said, no, we'll draw the lines.

620
00:54:07,749 --> 00:54:11,672
[SPEAKER_07]: will decide where the congressional districts will be.

621
00:54:12,212 --> 00:54:14,994
[SPEAKER_07]: So that's the latest coming out of there.

622
00:54:15,735 --> 00:54:18,697
[SPEAKER_07]: And the same thing can happen on a statewide or citywide basis.

623
00:54:20,578 --> 00:54:22,580
[SPEAKER_07]: It's the same idea, equal representation.

624
00:54:24,241 --> 00:54:32,667
[SPEAKER_07]: You want to draw your precincts in such a way that you have a relatively equal number of people in each precinct.

625
00:54:32,727 --> 00:54:36,230
[SPEAKER_14]: Thanks.

626
00:54:39,384 --> 00:54:43,965
[SPEAKER_14]: I think, Ron, you can move on to the next slide, but I think Aubrey had a question.

627
00:54:43,985 --> 00:54:45,105
[SPEAKER_09]: Yeah, go ahead.

628
00:54:45,905 --> 00:54:46,846
[SPEAKER_09]: I did have a question.

629
00:54:46,886 --> 00:54:48,826
[SPEAKER_09]: I'm thinking of this unequal workloads.

630
00:54:49,006 --> 00:55:00,489
[SPEAKER_09]: Did you all discuss the possibility or have any examples of it either working or not working for ward representatives having a different role than at-large representatives?

631
00:55:00,909 --> 00:55:04,129
[SPEAKER_09]: And if those, how they exist together?

632
00:55:04,149 --> 00:55:07,530
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah.

633
00:55:08,114 --> 00:55:20,005
[SPEAKER_05]: We did, in some of the out-of-city interviews, ward representation does have different connotations for different cities.

634
00:55:20,105 --> 00:55:32,216
[SPEAKER_05]: And, you know, Malden, for instance, has each ward rep has a budget, a small budget to, you know, do things that they want to do for their wards.

635
00:55:34,818 --> 00:55:35,838
[SPEAKER_05]: But I didn't hear any.

636
00:55:36,938 --> 00:55:42,360
[SPEAKER_05]: The only thing I heard from the interview with the city of Malden was that ward representation works really well for them.

637
00:55:42,401 --> 00:55:44,361
[SPEAKER_05]: And they didn't mention anything about the unequal.

638
00:55:45,002 --> 00:55:48,223
[SPEAKER_05]: Gene mentioned where most of that question came from.

639
00:55:48,283 --> 00:55:50,003
[SPEAKER_05]: And it may be true and it may not be true.

640
00:55:51,284 --> 00:55:55,266
[SPEAKER_05]: But I don't have any more specifics than that.

641
00:55:55,286 --> 00:56:01,428
[SPEAKER_05]: I don't know if I answered your question or not.

642
00:56:06,011 --> 00:56:12,474
[SPEAKER_05]: All right, so I will update that with John's changes there if we're all set to move on.

643
00:56:12,494 --> 00:56:16,635
[SPEAKER_05]: Yep.

644
00:56:18,036 --> 00:56:24,159
[SPEAKER_05]: Again, this is, if you don't vote for a ward candidate who gets elected, will they serve your needs?

645
00:56:24,179 --> 00:56:32,402
[SPEAKER_05]: I mean, you may agree or disagree with that statement, but

646
00:56:34,369 --> 00:56:35,810
[SPEAKER_05]: It's out there.

647
00:56:35,830 --> 00:56:40,514
[SPEAKER_14]: I think it's worth saying, yeah.

648
00:56:40,955 --> 00:56:41,155
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah.

649
00:56:41,315 --> 00:56:45,098
[SPEAKER_05]: And I do believe this came through the interview process too, Milwa, is that correct?

650
00:56:45,639 --> 00:56:46,119
[SPEAKER_14]: I don't know.

651
00:56:46,139 --> 00:56:49,081
[SPEAKER_14]: I thought it did.

652
00:56:49,241 --> 00:56:50,663
[SPEAKER_14]: Not from anybody I interviewed.

653
00:56:51,403 --> 00:56:51,724
[SPEAKER_05]: Okay.

654
00:56:52,284 --> 00:56:53,605
[SPEAKER_14]: But yeah.

655
00:56:54,906 --> 00:56:55,126
[SPEAKER_05]: All right.

656
00:56:55,687 --> 00:56:56,748
[SPEAKER_05]: Any questions on that one?

657
00:56:58,769 --> 00:57:00,451
[SPEAKER_11]: Yeah.

658
00:57:00,751 --> 00:57:02,072
[SPEAKER_05]: Good.

659
00:57:02,212 --> 00:57:02,973
[SPEAKER_05]: Who's talking?

660
00:57:04,253 --> 00:57:05,694
[SPEAKER_15]: Maybe a question mark after?

661
00:57:07,676 --> 00:57:09,137
[SPEAKER_02]: Well, basically, yes.

662
00:57:11,059 --> 00:57:19,485
[SPEAKER_08]: And maybe we should say, because they don't know who you voted for, but if you work for the opposing candidate, will your ward?

663
00:57:19,505 --> 00:57:21,567
[SPEAKER_08]: It's more of that, I think.

664
00:57:21,887 --> 00:57:23,368
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah, that's what I had mentioned before.

665
00:57:23,388 --> 00:57:23,468
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah.

666
00:57:24,990 --> 00:57:29,053
[SPEAKER_13]: Is the concern because it's not a multi-member race, there'll be retaliation?

667
00:57:30,234 --> 00:57:35,996
[SPEAKER_05]: No, it's a concern of, I chose one candidate over you, now I'm coming to you to ask a question.

668
00:57:36,036 --> 00:57:37,656
[SPEAKER_05]: Maybe I don't feel comfortable with that.

669
00:57:38,576 --> 00:57:39,997
[SPEAKER_05]: I don't think it's any more than that.

670
00:57:40,957 --> 00:57:45,078
[SPEAKER_08]: Or maybe the elected person doesn't want to talk to you.

671
00:57:45,098 --> 00:57:47,039
[SPEAKER_05]: Oh, they've reversed, correct.

672
00:57:47,279 --> 00:57:47,519
[SPEAKER_08]: Yeah.

673
00:57:48,079 --> 00:57:56,902
[SPEAKER_10]: Or won't take your, yeah, what Francis just said, the perceived power dynamic, or they won't take you seriously, or they'll, you know,

674
00:57:58,032 --> 00:57:59,752
[SPEAKER_10]: It gives you a little short shrift.

675
00:58:00,092 --> 00:58:02,593
[SPEAKER_13]: Yeah, I'll look into that.

676
00:58:02,913 --> 00:58:03,673
[SPEAKER_10]: And they never did.

677
00:58:03,953 --> 00:58:05,893
[SPEAKER_13]: I'm sorry to talk over you.

678
00:58:06,013 --> 00:58:08,034
[SPEAKER_13]: I'm sorry, say again?

679
00:58:08,074 --> 00:58:11,114
[SPEAKER_13]: Couldn't that happen now under our current large system?

680
00:58:11,194 --> 00:58:12,615
[SPEAKER_08]: Right, it does.

681
00:58:13,395 --> 00:58:14,335
[SPEAKER_13]: That's what I mean.

682
00:58:14,375 --> 00:58:17,135
[SPEAKER_13]: So how is it a con for this?

683
00:58:17,775 --> 00:58:25,237
[SPEAKER_05]: Well, because your attack would be focused on the person that you perceive is your ward rep.

684
00:58:27,388 --> 00:58:30,230
[SPEAKER_05]: So it's more fine-tuned, I'm guessing.

685
00:58:30,270 --> 00:58:31,190
[SPEAKER_05]: This is not my opinion.

686
00:58:31,250 --> 00:58:32,371
[SPEAKER_05]: Again, I'm just trying to explain.

687
00:58:32,391 --> 00:58:33,371
[SPEAKER_13]: Oh, no, no, I know.

688
00:58:33,631 --> 00:58:34,432
[SPEAKER_13]: I'm just trying to understand.

689
00:58:34,452 --> 00:58:36,112
[SPEAKER_10]: More of a narrow window.

690
00:58:36,192 --> 00:58:41,355
[SPEAKER_10]: I mean, right now you have seven councillors to go to with your concern.

691
00:58:41,435 --> 00:58:53,381
[SPEAKER_10]: If councillor number one doesn't get back to you or whatever, or you don't have a good rapport with them, then you

692
00:58:53,929 --> 00:58:57,050
[SPEAKER_10]: you know, go to counselor number two and so on and so forth.

693
00:58:57,210 --> 00:59:00,351
[SPEAKER_13]: So that's a really great thought, I think.

694
00:59:00,631 --> 00:59:03,252
[SPEAKER_13]: I didn't get that, but what you just said makes sense to me.

695
00:59:04,152 --> 00:59:07,634
[SPEAKER_13]: Maybe we could refine that.

696
00:59:07,654 --> 00:59:10,114
[SPEAKER_13]: I'll mediate on that.

697
00:59:11,155 --> 00:59:12,175
[SPEAKER_07]: Can I comment on that?

698
00:59:12,595 --> 00:59:12,855
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah.

699
00:59:13,276 --> 00:59:16,697
[SPEAKER_07]: And I'm going to go back to my own personal experience.

700
00:59:19,392 --> 00:59:22,914
[SPEAKER_07]: If people perceive, maybe they didn't vote for me, how would I know that?

701
00:59:23,034 --> 00:59:28,496
[SPEAKER_07]: But maybe they worked for my opponent and they perceived that I wouldn't want to take a telephone call from them.

702
00:59:29,197 --> 00:59:47,165
[SPEAKER_07]: If it was a, um, you had at large elected city councilors as well, then you would have, depending on how many boards you have, three or four at large councilors who you also voted for and who also represent you, who you could call.

703
00:59:48,553 --> 01:00:08,099
[SPEAKER_07]: I think the answer to the question is really personality driven by both the person and the counselor, because I always saw my getting a call from somebody who I understood didn't like me as an opportunity to change that person around.

704
01:00:08,119 --> 01:00:17,422
[SPEAKER_07]: Now, whatever they wanted, that issue with trash pickup, they'd like a tree in front of the house, wanted to talk about when the street could get paved,

705
01:00:18,361 --> 01:00:21,764
[SPEAKER_07]: If I had that opportunity to speak to that person, I always was happy to do it.

706
01:00:22,604 --> 01:00:27,868
[SPEAKER_07]: And sometimes it changed them, and sometimes it might not have, but a lot of times I probably didn't know.

707
01:00:28,028 --> 01:00:31,511
[SPEAKER_07]: But I really think it depends on the individual.

708
01:00:32,172 --> 01:00:36,735
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't think you can stereotype the position and the people who hold it.

709
01:00:36,795 --> 01:00:38,296
[SPEAKER_05]: No, not at all.

710
01:00:38,496 --> 01:00:39,057
[SPEAKER_05]: I agree with you.

711
01:00:40,106 --> 01:00:49,834
[SPEAKER_15]: I agree with a lot of which Frank said that it's always the opportunity to work with somebody who you know wasn't your original supporter.

712
01:00:50,895 --> 01:01:01,123
[SPEAKER_15]: I do think if you're gonna include this one, you should write if you don't support a ward candidate who gets selected as opposed to vote because nobody really knows who you voted for.

713
01:01:01,143 --> 01:01:03,565
[SPEAKER_15]: I would suggest the word support.

714
01:01:05,007 --> 01:01:08,650
[SPEAKER_14]: Anthony from the Collins Center also wanted to make a comment.

715
01:01:09,818 --> 01:01:19,952
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah, I just wanted to interject a little bit, sort of more broadly about this pros versus cons section, because it took me a little while to wrap my head around it.

716
01:01:21,074 --> 01:01:27,057
[SPEAKER_04]: And I guess as I understand it, this committee has conducted interviews and spoken to people and done surveys.

717
01:01:27,537 --> 01:01:31,698
[SPEAKER_04]: And some of these things have come out of that process.

718
01:01:32,219 --> 01:01:44,644
[SPEAKER_04]: So I think it may not be the best framing as pros versus cons versus concerns or thoughts that have been developed because it

719
01:01:45,953 --> 01:01:53,837
[SPEAKER_04]: The way the presentation at least appeared to me was that the committee at first was taking a position on this is a pro or this is a con.

720
01:01:54,098 --> 01:01:55,898
[SPEAKER_04]: And maybe that's not how you want to present it.

721
01:01:55,919 --> 01:02:01,762
[SPEAKER_04]: Maybe you just want to present that you've heard these things and you want to bring them to the forefront in the community discussion.

722
01:02:02,642 --> 01:02:07,345
[SPEAKER_04]: If I'm understanding the presentation and how it's been brought forward.

723
01:02:08,417 --> 01:02:13,298
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah, it's definitely not the opinion of this committee for these pros and cons.

724
01:02:13,358 --> 01:02:17,719
[SPEAKER_05]: It's just that we just, you know, we just vetted as best we could what those were.

725
01:02:17,759 --> 01:02:18,739
[SPEAKER_05]: I understand what you're saying.

726
01:02:18,779 --> 01:02:19,760
[SPEAKER_05]: This is not the opinion.

727
01:02:19,800 --> 01:02:24,140
[SPEAKER_05]: Maybe that's, maybe that's what we need to put up front is this is not the opinion of the committee.

728
01:02:25,781 --> 01:02:27,561
[SPEAKER_05]: Show how it was gathered with a disclaimer.

729
01:02:29,682 --> 01:02:30,042
[SPEAKER_14]: Okay.

730
01:02:30,962 --> 01:02:31,222
[SPEAKER_14]: Thanks.

731
01:02:31,262 --> 01:02:32,202
[SPEAKER_14]: That's a great comment.

732
01:02:32,282 --> 01:02:32,642
[SPEAKER_14]: Thank you.

733
01:02:32,682 --> 01:02:35,623
[SPEAKER_14]: And thank you, Francis, for the comment that you gave as well.

734
01:02:36,564 --> 01:02:38,985
[SPEAKER_05]: Is everybody, is there anybody online waiting?

735
01:02:40,065 --> 01:02:41,586
[SPEAKER_05]: Okay.

736
01:02:43,367 --> 01:02:46,728
[SPEAKER_05]: Board representation may limit voter candidate options.

737
01:02:52,250 --> 01:02:52,531
[SPEAKER_05]: Yes.

738
01:02:55,192 --> 01:02:58,213
[SPEAKER_14]: This goes back to not having as many people to vote for.

739
01:02:59,300 --> 01:03:17,851
[SPEAKER_05]: Uh, it has to do with that and it also has to do with, um, you know, uh, I I'm guessing it also has to do with if there are four candidates in a certain ward, uh, right now, um, those four, uh, need to make decisions, whether they're going to be the ward rep or be the at large rep.

740
01:03:17,931 --> 01:03:22,474
[SPEAKER_05]: So, um, if, uh, and it was mentioned in some.

741
01:03:23,394 --> 01:03:41,787
[SPEAKER_05]: research that we did, if there are three incumbent candidates in Ward 3, for instance, and two decide to run for ward rep, only one can make it, which means you lose an option for that incumbent rep based on the fact that they chose to run for ward versus at-large.

742
01:03:46,570 --> 01:03:47,711
[SPEAKER_12]: But that would be their choice.

743
01:03:48,461 --> 01:03:48,981
[SPEAKER_05]: Absolutely.

744
01:03:49,742 --> 01:03:55,945
[SPEAKER_05]: But it's still, it's still, you know, it's different from the at-large scenario, which they don't have to make that choice.

745
01:03:59,047 --> 01:04:02,268
[SPEAKER_05]: That's all that's talking about.

746
01:04:02,288 --> 01:04:02,568
[SPEAKER_14]: Okay.

747
01:04:03,209 --> 01:04:03,609
[SPEAKER_05]: Okay.

748
01:04:06,871 --> 01:04:08,351
[SPEAKER_05]: This was a clear statement.

749
01:04:08,411 --> 01:04:11,193
[SPEAKER_05]: The purpose of the city council is to represent the whole city.

750
01:04:11,213 --> 01:04:14,995
[SPEAKER_05]: I think that assumes a lot in that con, but it's a con.

751
01:04:18,952 --> 01:04:20,273
[SPEAKER_08]: Can I add a little bit more here?

752
01:04:20,293 --> 01:04:21,853
[SPEAKER_02]: You certainly can.

753
01:04:22,754 --> 01:04:25,695
[SPEAKER_08]: But I can't remember if this goes to this one, so let me know, Ron.

754
01:04:26,255 --> 01:04:26,555
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah.

755
01:04:26,876 --> 01:04:41,702
[SPEAKER_08]: There's some research that we looked at that across MIT, I think, looked at multiple cities that went from at-large to ward representation or ward hybrid.

756
01:04:41,722 --> 01:04:42,642
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah.

757
01:04:43,302 --> 01:04:46,964
[SPEAKER_08]: And housing production in those cities

758
01:04:48,061 --> 01:04:49,042
[SPEAKER_08]: overall decreased by 20%.

759
01:04:49,222 --> 01:05:07,270
[SPEAKER_08]: And they attributed it partly to ward representatives being more focused on their neighborhood and wanting to be less concerned about, say, housing production overall and wanting to preserve their neighborhood.

760
01:05:08,471 --> 01:05:10,272
[SPEAKER_08]: Milved, would you add anything to that?

761
01:05:10,332 --> 01:05:10,532
[SPEAKER_08]: Or am I

762
01:05:11,355 --> 01:05:14,217
